imply /ɪmˈplaɪ/

(implying,implied,implies) 

1. V-T If you imply that something is the case, you say something that indicates that it is the case in an indirect way. 暗指 

例： 'Are you implying that I have something to do with those attacks?' she asked coldly. “你在暗指我和那些袭击有关吗？”她冷冷地问道。 

2. V-T If an event or situation implies that something is the case, it makes you think that it is the case. 意味着 

例： Exports in June rose 1.5%, implying that the economy was stronger than many investors had realized. 6月份的出口额增加了1.5%，这意味着经济比许多投资者所了解的要强劲。

</div>

